<section>
	<title>Introduction to Modeling</title>

	<p><xref provisional="WORK-IN-PROGRESS"/></p>
	
	<p>
		Many times, a quantity is connected to how it changes (its derivative). When these connections are expressed mathematically, they result in a differential equation. For example, consider this statement:
		<blockquote>
			<p>
				<em>The rate of change of a function is equal to the function itself.</em>
			</p>
		</blockquote>
	</p>

	<p>
		Mathematically, if we give this function a name, say <m>y</m>, this statement can be transformed into a differential equation, as shown.
		<blockquote>
			<p>
				<em>The <m>\color{blue}\underset{y^\prime}{\fbox{rate of change of a function}}</m> <m>\underset{=}{\fbox{is equal}}</m> to the <m>\color{green}\underset{y}{\fbox{function}}</m> itself.</em>
			</p>
		</blockquote>
		<me> y' = y. </me>
	</p>

	<p>
		A <q>solution</q> to this differential equation would be any function equal to its own derivative. Do you know a function like that?
		<fn>Since <m>\ds\frac{d}{dx}\left[e^x\right] = e^x</m> then <m>y=e^x</m> is a solution!</fn>
	</p>

	<p>
		Here is another example from physics:
		<blockquote>
			<p>
				<em>A force acting on an object is equal to the object's mass (constant) multiplied by its acceleration.</em>
			</p>
		</blockquote>
	</p>

	<p>
		If we let <m>F(t)</m> be the force on the object, <m>y(t)</m> be the position of the object, and remembering that acceleration is the second derivative of position, then this statement can be written as the differential equation
		<me> F(t) = mass \cdot y''(t) </me>.
		The solution to this differential equation would involve finding the position function <m>y(t)</m>.
	</p>
	
	<reading-questions><title>Check-Point Questions</title>

		<exercise><title><em>Statement <m>\to</m> DE 1</em></title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Which equation below best represents the statement:
					<blockquote>
						<p>
							The rate of change of a population <m> P </m> is equal to a constant times the population itself.
						</p>
					</blockquote>
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices randomize="yes">
				<choice>
					<statement><m> P' = k </m></statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. This represents a constant rate of change, not one proportional to the population.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement><m> P' = kP </m></statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Correct. The rate of change is equal to a constant times the population itself.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement><m> P = k </m></statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. This does not represent the relationship given in the statement.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement><m> P'' = kP </m></statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. This represents a second derivative relationship.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</exercise>
		
		<exercise><title><em>Statement <m>\to</m> DE 2</em></title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Which equation below best represents the statement:
					<blockquote>
						<p>
							The acceleration of a car, with position <m> s(t) </m>, is equal to a constant, <m>k</m>, times the velocity of the car.
						</p>
					</blockquote>
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices randomize="yes">
				<choice>
					<statement><m> s'(t) = k </m></statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. This indicates that velocity is constant.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement><m> s'(t) = ks''(t) </m></statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. This indicates that velocity is a constant times acceleration.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement><m> s''(t) = ks(t) </m></statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. This indicates that acceleration is a constant times position.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement><m> s''(t) = ks''(t) </m></statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Correct. The acceleration is equal to a constant times the velocity.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</exercise>
		
		<exercise><title><em>Statement <m>\to</m> DE 3</em></title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Which equation below best represents the statement:
					<blockquote>
						<p>
							The rate at which a substance cools is equal to a constant times the difference between its temperature <m> T(t) </m> and the ambient temperature <m> T_a </m>.
						</p>
					</blockquote>
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices randomize="yes">
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement><m> T'(t) = k(T(t) - T_a) </m></statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Correct. The rate of cooling is equal to a constant times the temperature difference.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement><m> T''(t) = k(T(t) - T_a) </m></statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. This represents a second derivative relationship.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement><m> T(t) = k(T(t) - T_a) </m></statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. This does not represent the rate of change.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement><m> T'(t) = kT(t) </m></statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. This implies the rate of change is directly proportional to the temperature, not the temperature difference.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</exercise>
		
		<exercise><title><em>Statement <m>\to</m> Differential Equation</em></title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Which equation below best represents the statement:
					<blockquote>
						<p>
							The rate of decay of a radioactive substance <m> N </m> is equal to a constant times the amount of the substance.
						</p>
					</blockquote>
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices randomize="yes">
				<choice>
					<statement><m> N' = kN </m></statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. This represents growth, not decay.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement><m> N'' = kN </m></statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. This represents a second derivative relationship.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement><m> N' = -kN </m></statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Correct. The rate of decay is equal to a negative constant times the amount of the substance.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement><m> N = kN' </m></statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. This does not represent the rate of change.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</exercise>
		
		<exercise><title><em>Statement <m>\to</m> Differential Equation</em></title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Which equation below best represents the statement:
					<blockquote>
						<p>
							The rate of change of the amount of money <m> M(t) </m> in a bank account is equal to a constant times the amount of money in the account.
						</p>
					</blockquote>
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices randomize="yes">
				<choice>
					<statement><m> M'(t) = k </m></statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. This represents a constant rate of change, not one dependent on the amount of money.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement><m> M(t) = kM'(t) </m></statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. This does not represent the rate of change.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement><m> M'(t) = kM(t) </m></statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Correct. The rate of change is equal to a constant times the amount of money in the account.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement><m> M''(t) = kM(t) </m></statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. This represents a second derivative relationship.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</exercise>
		
		<exercise><title><em>Statement <m>\to</m> Differential Equation</em></title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Which equation below best represents the statement:
					<blockquote>
						<p>
							The velocity of an object with position, <m>s(t)</m>, in free fall is equal to a constant times the time <m> t </m>.
						</p>
					</blockquote>
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices randomize="yes">
				<choice>
					<statement><m> s(t) = gt </m></statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. This says the position is equal to a constant times the time.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement><m> s'(t) = gt + C </m></statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The statement says nothing about adding a constant, <m>C</m>.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement><m> s'(t) = gt </m></statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Correct.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement><m> s''(t) = gt </m></statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. <m>s''(t)</m> is acceleration, not velocity.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</exercise>
		
	</reading-questions>

</section>